<div class="hatnote">For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Ballast_(disambiguation)" title="Ballast (disambiguation)" class="mw-disambig">Ballast (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<p><b>Ballast</b> is used in <a href="/wiki/Sailboat" title="Sailboat">sailboats</a> to provide <a href="/wiki/Moment_(physics)" title="Moment (physics)">moment</a> to resist the lateral forces on the <a href="/wiki/Sail" title="Sail">sail</a>. Insufficiently ballasted boats will tend to tip, or heel, excessively in high winds. Too much heel may result in the boat <a href="/wiki/Capsize" title="Capsize" class="mw-redirect">capsizing</a>. If a sailing vessel should need to voyage without cargo then ballast of little or no value would be loaded to keep the vessel upright. Some or all of this ballast would then be discarded when cargo was loaded.</p>
